\begin_layout Subsection
Symmetric spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This and the next two sections shamelessly stolen from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Harland16"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a compact connected Lie group.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p:G\to G$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(gg^{\prime}\right)=p\left(g\right)p\left(g^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 and also 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}\left(g\right)=p\left(p\left(g\right)\right)=g$
\end_inset

.
 The fixed points 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in G$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(h\right)=h$
\end_inset

.
 These form a subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H\subset G$
\end_inset

 and the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 is a symmetric space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This function 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 will be later be used as a kind of parity operator, or a symmetrizer, and
 will be used to define the vector and axial vector built from chiral fields.
 For now, there is no need to appeal to this, so we will proceed in a general
 setting for as long as possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 be the correspoding Lie algbera of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 descends to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 the identity, it's eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 It splits 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 into odd and even subspaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}=\mathfrak{m}\oplus\mathfrak{h}$
\end_inset

 The odd-parity subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 can be identified as the tangent space of 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 at the identity and the even-parity subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{h}$
\end_inset

 is the Lie algebra of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 Note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathfrak{h},\mathfrak{h}\right]\subseteq\mathfrak{h}\quad\mbox{ and }\quad\left[\mathfrak{m},\mathfrak{h}\right]\subseteq\mathfrak{m}\quad\mbox{ and }\quad\left[\mathfrak{m},\mathfrak{m}\right]\mathfrak{\subseteq h}
\]

\end_inset

The easiest way to see this is to note that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left[X,Y\right]=\left[p\left(X\right),p\left(Y\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y\in\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $X=X_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus X_{\mathfrak{h}}$
\end_inset

 and note the 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(X_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus X_{\mathfrak{h}}\right)=\left(-X_{\mathfrak{m}}\right)\oplus X_{\mathfrak{h}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then clearly the parity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[X_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus0,0\oplus Y_{\mathfrak{h}}\right]$
\end_inset

 is negative, while the parity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0\oplus X_{\mathfrak{h}},0\oplus Y_{\mathfrak{h}}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[X_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus0,Y_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus0\right]$
\end_inset

 is positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two more identities are useful.
 The adjoint action 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ad}_{g}X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 behaves as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(\mbox{Ad}_{g}X\right)=p\left(gXg^{-1}\right)=p\left(g\right)p\left(X\right)p\left(g^{-1}\right)=\mbox{Ad}_{p\left(g\right)}p\left(X\right)
\]

\end_inset

Given a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:\mathbb{R}\to G$
\end_inset

 on the group manifold, the tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\gamma^{-1}\partial_{t}\gamma$
\end_inset

 to the curve transforms as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(\gamma^{-1}\partial_{t}\gamma\right)=p\left(\gamma^{-1}\right)\partial_{t}p\left(\gamma\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Vector and Gauge fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be a spin manifold.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:M\to G/H$
\end_inset

 the physical field, with 
\begin_inset Formula $g:M\to G$
\end_inset

 a section of the principle bundle of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 ovre 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $h:M\to H$
\end_inset

 be a gauge transformation.
 Define the even and odd parity vector and axial vector fields as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{\mu}=\pi_{\mathfrak{m}}\circ\left(g^{-1}\partial_{\mu}g\right)\quad\mbox{ and }\quad A_{\mu}=\pi_{\mathfrak{h}}\circ\left(g^{-1}\partial_{\mu}g\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathfrak{h}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 are the projections 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathfrak{h}}:\mathfrak{g}\to\mathfrak{h}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathfrak{m}}:\mathfrak{g}\to\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Under gauge transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $g\to gh$
\end_inset

, these transform as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{\mu}\mapsto h^{-1}L_{\mu}h\quad\mbox{ and }\quad A_{\mu}\mapsto h^{-1}A_{\mu}h+h^{-1}\partial_{\mu}h
\]

\end_inset

The easiest way to see this is to explicitly write 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}\partial_{\mu}g=X_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{\mu}\mapsto h^{-1}X_{\mu}h+h^{-1}\partial_{\mu}h
\]

\end_inset

By definition, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-1}\partial_{\mu}h\in\mathfrak{h}$
\end_inset

 and likewise by defintion that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathfrak{m}}\left(\mathfrak{h}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and so in performing the projection 
\begin_inset Formula $X=X_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus X_{\mathfrak{h}}=\pi_{\mathfrak{m}}\left(X\right)\oplus\pi_{\mathfrak{h}}\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 the above forms necessarily follow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 transforms as a differential 1-form, while 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 transforms as a gauge field; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is the affine connection (on the tangent bundle of 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Chiral vector fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The standard chiral interpretation is to take the vector and axial-vector
 spaces as the diagonal and modulo spaces of a product of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

left
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

right
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 chiral fields.
 Write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=H\times H
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(h_{L},h_{R}\right)=\left(h_{R},h_{L}\right)$
\end_inset

 the permutation of the two elements satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 and thus can be used as a symmetrizer to split out the diagonal.
 The fixed points are 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(h,h\right)=\left(h,h\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H=\left(H\times H\right)/H$
\end_inset

 is diffeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, the explicit diffeomorphism is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(h_{L},h_{R}\right)\mapsto U=h_{L}h_{R}^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

All products of compact connected Lie groups work like this – the diagonal
 is a symmetric space diffeomorphic to the group itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given bases vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{h}$
\end_inset

 we can write an explicit basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(e_{i},-e_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 which corresponds to the 
\begin_inset Formula $p=-1$
\end_inset

 eigenspace, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(e_{i},e_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 as the basis for the 
\begin_inset Formula $p=+1$
\end_inset

 eigenspace.
 These two are the axial-vector and the vector subspaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The historical basis for this chiral split is anchored in beta decay; the
 weak interactions distinguish left from right.
 This implied that the flavor symmetries must also have chiral components.
\end_layout

